        "excerpt": "Now I, Paul, myself urge you by the meekness and gentleness of Christ — I who am meek when face to face with you, but bold toward you when absent!",
        "body": "Paul's opening sentence is loaded. *Now I, Paul, myself* (autos egō Paulos) is one of the most emphatic self-identifications in the corpus, reserved for moments of personal stake (cf. Galatians 5:2; Philemon 19). The corporate *we* of chapters 1-9 falls away; the apostle steps forward in his own person to confront opponents who have made him personally the issue.\n\nHe appeals *by the meekness and gentleness of Christ*. This is not throat-clearing — it is a programmatic frame. *Prautēs* (meekness) and *epieikeia* (gentleness, forbearance, reasonableness) are the very qualities Jesus claimed in Matthew 11:29 (*I am gentle and humble in heart*) and which Aristotle praised as the virtue of the magnanimous man who does not stand on every right (*Nicomachean Ethics* 5.10). Paul invokes them because his opponents have been using his very meekness against him: they read it as weakness, and they have weaponized the contrast between his demeanor in person and his boldness on paper.\n\nThat charge is preserved almost verbatim in 10:1b — *I who am meek when face to face with you, but bold toward you when absent*. The Greek is ironic; Paul is not confessing a fault but parroting the slander. The intruders had constructed a portrait of two different Pauls: a gentle, hesitant figure in person (whose ministerial weakness disqualified him), and an aggressive, threatening figure on paper (whose letters they wished to dismiss). Paul will dismantle this portrait at 10:11 by insisting on the continuity of word and deed.\n\nVerse 2 raises the stakes. Paul *begs* (deomai — the language of urgent entreaty) that when he comes he may not need to be bold with the confidence he intends to exercise *against some, who regard us as if we walked according to the flesh*. The subgroup is named indirectly: the intruders and their sympathizers. The charge — *kata sarka peripatountas* (walking according to the flesh) — is what the next four verses will surgically rebut.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Prautēs* is the meekness that does not retaliate (cf. Matthew 5:5); *epieikeia* is the disposition that does not insist on the strict letter of one's rights — a magistrate's virtue in Greco-Roman ethics, here predicated of Christ. The pairing appears in Plutarch and Philo, but Paul roots it in Christology, not philosophy."
